@startuml service_sync
!theme plain

skinparam backgroundColor white
skinparam sequenceArrowThickness 2
skinparam sequenceParticipantPadding 30
skinparam sequenceBoxPadding 10
skinparam noteFontSize 11

title ROS 2 Service Communication (Sync Client)

box "Client Process" #lightyellow
  participant "Timer Callback\n(default group)" as Timer
  participant "Service Client\n(separate group)" as SClient
end box

participant "MultiThreadedExecutor" as Exec
participant "Server Node" as Server

== Initialization ==

note over Timer, SClient
  Client uses **two callback groups**:
  • Timer → default MutuallyExclusiveCallbackGroup
  • Service client → separate MutuallyExclusiveCallbackGroup
  Must use **MultiThreadedExecutor** so both can run concurrently.
end note

== Request/Response (Sync) ==

Exec -> Timer : _timer_callback()
activate Timer

Timer -> SClient : self._client.call(request)
activate SClient
note right of Timer #salmon : **Blocks this thread**\nuntil response arrives

SClient -> Server : request
activate Server

Server -> Server : _service_callback(\nrequest, response)

Server --> SClient : response
deactivate Server

SClient --> Timer : response
deactivate SClient
note right of Timer : Thread unblocked.\nProcess response.

deactivate Timer

== Deadlock Scenario ==

note over Timer, Exec #salmon
  **DEADLOCK** if any of these are missing:
  1. Service client not in a **separate callback group**
  2. Not using a **MultiThreadedExecutor**
  → The blocked timer thread holds the only executor thread,
    so the response can never be delivered.
end note

@enduml
